==Old English==
===Etymology 1===
From Germanic ''*limu-'', probably related to ''*liþu-'' ( > [[liþ]]).  Cognate with Old Norse [[limr]].

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA|/lɪm/}}

====Noun====
'''lim''' ''n'' (plural '''[[limu]]''')
# [[limb]], bodily member; [[branch]] (of tree etc)

====Descendants====
*English: [[limb]]

===Etymology 2===
From Germanic ''*leimaz'', from Indo-European ''*lei-''.  Cognate with Middle Dutch [[lim#Middle Dutch|līm]] (Dutch [[lijm]]), Old High German [[lim#Old High German|līm]] (German [[Leim]]), Old Norse [[lím]] (Swedish [[lim]]).  The PIE root is also the source of Latin [[limus]] ‘mud’.

====Pronunciation====
{{IPA|/li:m/}}

====Noun====
{{Unicode|'''līm'''}} ''m'' (plural '''[[limas|līmas]]''')
# [[mortar]], [[paste]], [[lime]]

====Descendants====
*English: [[lime]]

